data.content:
## What Breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider allowed synchronous operations via an explicit **sync-over-async opt-in** (`CosmosOptionsExtension` / `EnableSyncOverAsync`). In .NET 11 (EF Core 11), that opt-in is **removed entirely**. The Cosmos DB provider is now **async-only**.

Every synchronous call in your repository will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime:

| Breaks | Replacement |
|---|---|
| `.ToList()` | `.ToListAsync()` |
| `.First(...)` | `.FirstAsync(...)` |
| `.Count()` | `.CountAsync()` |
| `.SaveChanges()` | `.SaveChangesAsync()` |

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- The `EnableSyncOverAsync` configuration option no longer exists — setting it will cause a build error.
- Callers of these methods must also be updated to `await` the results (`async` propagates up the call chain).
- `Add()` remains synchronous (it only tracks in-memory); the I/O happens in `SaveChangesAsync()`.
